# Sample dataframe got1 with columns source.family and target.family

# Define the allowed family names
allowed_names <- c("Targaryen", "Stark", "Greyjoy", "Tully", "Lannister", "Baratheon", "Arryn", "Tyrell")

# Filter the dataframe to only include rows where source.family or target.family is in the allowed_names list
filtered_got1 <- got1 %>%
  filter(Source.Family %in% allowed_names, Target.Family %in% allowed_names)



# create an undirected network object
got1.net <- graph_from_data_frame(filtered_got1, directed = F)
# un_net <- graph_from_data_frame(edges, directed = F, vertices = nodes)

is.simple(got1.net)
## Warning: `is.simple()` was deprecated in igraph 2.0.0.
## ℹ Please use `is_simple()` instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
## [1] TRUE
library(ggraph)
library(ggplot2)

family_colors <- c("Stark" = "azure2", "Lannister" = "red", "Baratheon" = "yellow", "Tully" = "maroon", "Targaryen" = "black", "Greyjoy" = "deepskyblue3", "Arryn" = "blue", "Tyrell" = "darkgreen")

# Assign colors and labels to nodes
V(got1.net)$color <- sapply(V(got1.net)$name, function(node_name) {
  source_family <- got1$Source.Family[got1$Source == node_name][1]
  if(source_family %in% names(family_colors)) {
    return(family_colors[source_family])
  } else {
    return("grey")  # Default color for families not in the top 5
  }
})
V(got1.net)$group <- got1$Source.Family[match(V(got1.net)$name, got1$Source)]
V(got1.net)$label <- V(got1.net)$name

# Layout emphasizing group clustering
layout <- create_layout(got1.net, layout = "with_fr")

## [1] 0.17

## [1] 0.22
cent_deg5 <- centralization.degree(got5.net, mode = "all")$centralization
round(cent_deg5, digits = 2)
## [1] 0.18

this analysis tells us that in book 1 there was high centralization (focus on one main family/character) then as books progressed there were more main characeters and families involved, less of a focus on a single influencial family
